04698nam a22005655i 9780822380047DE-B159720220729113935.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220729t20012000ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223800477 a10.1515/97808223800472doi  a(DE-B1597)553229  a(OCoLC)51906030  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aHC177.B82bA89 2001eb 7aHIS0330002bisacsh04a322.4/4/09822211 aAuyero, Javier, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPoor People's Politics :bPeronist Survival Networks and the Legacy of Evita /cJavier Auyero. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2001] 4c©2000  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b1 table, 2 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tWho Is Who in the Peronist Network -- tIntroduction: The Day of the Rally -- t1. ‘‘They Were Mostly Poor People’’ -- t2. ‘‘Most of Them Were Comingfrom Villa Paraíso’’ -- t3. ‘‘They Knew Matilde’’ -- t4. ‘‘We Will Fight Forever,We Are Peronists’’ -- t5. The ‘‘Clientelist’’ Viewpoint -- t6. ‘‘They Were All Peronists’’ -- tConclusions -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a“Political clientelism” is a term used to characterize the contemporary relationships between political elites and the poor in Latin America in which goods and services are traded for political favors. Javier Auyero critically deploys the notion in Poor People’s Politics to analyze the political practices of the Peronist Party among shantytown dwellers in contemporary Argentina.Looking closely at the slum-dwellers’ informal problem-solving networks, which are necessary for material survival, and the different meanings of Peronism within these networks, Auyero presents the first ethnography of urban clientelism ever carried out in Argentina. Revealing a deep familiarity with the lives of the urban poor in Villa Paraíso, a stigmatized and destitute shantytown of Buenos Aires, Auyero demonstrates the ways in which local politicians present their vital favors to the poor and how the poor perceive and evaluate these favors. Having penetrated the networks, he describes how they are structured, what is traded, and the particular way in which women facilitate these transactions. Moreover, Auyero proposes that the act of granting favors or giving food in return for votes gives the politicians’ acts a performative and symbolic meaning that flavors the relation between problem-solver and problem-holder, while also creating quite different versions of contemporary Peronism. Along the way, Auyero is careful to situate the emergence and consolidation of clientelism in historic, cultural, and economic contexts.Poor People’s Politics reexamines the relationship between politics and the destitute in Latin America, showing how deeply embedded politics are in the lives of those who do not mobilize in the usual sense of the word but who are far from passive. It will appeal to a wide range of students and scholars of Latin American studies, sociology, anthropology, political science, history, and cultural studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aPatronage, PoliticalzArgentinazBuenos Aires. 0aPeronism. 0aPoorxPolitical activityzArgentinazBuenos Aires. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South America.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107118370 cprintz978082232627440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822380047?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822380047423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822380047/original  a978-3-11-071183-7  Duke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-201